I worked on a project called AAS â€“ Audio Announcement Service. Itâ€™s a customer-specific embedded application deployed in places like railway stations and trains. The main purpose of the system is to receive announcement instructions from a central backend, download the required audio files securely, and play them at the correct time on the correct speakers through the local public address system.â€
â€œThe device communicates with the backend using AMQP over a secure TLS connection with client certificates, so all communication is encrypted and authenticated. The backend sends us command messages called PDCC(Physical device command container). The most important ones are ANNOUT, which tells us to play an announcement, and ANNDEL, which cancels a previously scheduled announcement.â€
â€œAn ANNOUT message contains details like which speaker group to use, the priority of the announcement, when it should start, when it must end, a unique ID, a hash for file verification, and an HTTPS URL to download the audio file. The audio itself is not sent in the message â€” only the link.â€
â€œWhen we receive an ANNOUT, the first thing we do is validate it â€” we check the format, confirm the URL is HTTPS, verify it hasnâ€™t expired, and ensure the content type is correct. Then we download the audio file securely using mutual TLS, and verify the hash to ensure the file is not corrupted. After that, we store it in a local cache so we donâ€™t download the same file repeatedly.â€
â€œNext, we schedule the playback based on priority, start time, and deadline. High-priority announcements can interrupt lower-priority ones. To play the audio, our service communicates with the local audio controller hardware called ELISA III-IP using a message-queue based IPC mechanism. We send a serialized control structure that includes priority, channel, timing, and the local file path. ELISA then plays the announcement and sends back a response code indicating success or specific hardware errors.â€
â€œBased on that response, we send status back to the central system using PPM monitoring messages â€” either an acknowledgment for success or detailed error codes if something failed.â€
â€œWe also continuously monitor the health of the speaker lines. If any channel is defective, we report a DEGRADED state with the list of faulty channels. If everything is healthy, the state is RUNNING. If the entire device fails, we report FAULT.â€
â€œSecurity is a major part of the system. The device uses mutual TLS everywhere. Certificates are time-limited, so we automatically renew them. If a device has no valid certificate, we use a one-time token mechanism with device ID and pairing code to obtain a new one from the certificate service.â€
â€œOverall, the system is designed to be very robust. We implemented retries for network failures, de-duplication using sequence numbers, idempotent cancellation, detailed logging, and continuous monitoring. In short, AAS acts as the intelligent controller that ensures the right announcement plays at the right time on the right speakers, even when the network is unstable or some hardware components are partially failing.â€




